-- Hong Kong shares fall after weak China data, Chinese banks firm
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Thu Mar 13, 2014 04:06AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, March 13 (Reuters) - Hong Kong stocks ended lower on Thursday, thanks to disappointing China economic data in the afternoon that caused  an index of Chinese shares listed in the city to close at a fresh eight-month low.

China's industrial output growth came in below forecasts for the combined January/February period, with retail sales also weaker than expected, continuing a run of sluggish data from the world's second-largest economy. [ID:nL3N0M92FB] The benchmark Hang Seng Index <.HSI> ended down 0.7 percent at 21,756.1 points, the lowest close since Feb. 10. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the top offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong eased 0.4 percent to 9,322.9 points, the lowest close since July 10. [ID:nL3N0MA1S9] Chinese banks gained support on reports about an anticipated preferred shares pilot programme in the mainland that they could be the first ones to join. [ID:nL3N0M91UU]